04334nam a22006615i 9780804796385DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047963857 a10.1515/97808047963852doi  a(DE-B1597)563919  a(OCoLC)1198929669  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a297.4092aB2231 aHoesterey, James Bourk, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRebranding Islam :bPiety, Prosperity, and a Self-Help Guru /cJames Bourk Hoesterey. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Walter H. Shorenstein Asia-Pacific Research Center00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Authority, Subjectivity, and the Cultural Politics of Public Piety -- tChapter 1. Rebranding Islam -- tChapter 2. Enchanting Science -- tChapter 3. Ethical Entrepreneurs -- tChapter 4. Prophetic Cosmopolitanism -- tChapter 5. Shaming the State -- tChapter 6. Sincerity and Scandal -- tConclusion. Figuring Islam -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKyai Haji Abdullah Gymnastiar, known affectionately by Indonesians as "Aa Gym" (elder brother Gym), rose to fame via nationally televised sermons, best-selling books, and corporate training seminars. In Rebranding Islam James B. Hoesterey draws on two years' study of this charismatic leader and his message of Sufi ideas blended with Western pop psychology and management theory to examine new trends in the religious and economic desires of an aspiring middle class, the political predicaments bridging self and state, and the broader themes of religious authority, economic globalization, and the end(s) of political Islam. At Gymnastiar's Islamic school, television studios, and MQ Training complex, Hoesterey observed this charismatic preacher developing a training regimen called Manajemen Qolbu into Indonesia's leading self-help program via nationally televised sermons, best-selling books, and corporate training seminars. Hoesterey's analysis explains how Gymnastiar articulated and mobilized Islamic idioms of ethics and affect as a way to offer self-help solutions for Indonesia's moral, economic, and political problems. Hoesterey then shows how, after Aa Gym's fall, the former celebrity guru was eclipsed by other television preachers in what is the ever-changing mosaic of Islam in Indonesia. Although Rebranding Islam tells the story of one man, it is also an anthropology of Islamic psychology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCelebritieszIndonesiavBiography. 0aIslamxPsychology. 0aMuslim religious leaderszIndonesiavBiography. 0aMuslimsxReligious lifezIndonesia. 0aSelf-help techniquesxReligious aspects. 4aIndonesia. 4aIslam. 4aaffect. 4aemotion. 4amarketing. 4amedia. 4apolitics. 4apsychology. 4areligious authority. 4asubjectivity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479638540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804796385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804796385.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles